.Sh DESCRIPTION
.Nm
is a time-tracking CLI that lets you clock in and out of work sessions,
tracking how long you spend on each task.
It is designed for minimal overhead so that you can focus on work and
still accurately track your time.
.Pp
All durations are stored internally in seconds for precision.
Timestamps use ISO 8601 format
.Pq Ql %Y\-%m\-%dT%H:%M:%S
and are always in the local time zone.
Simplified forms are accepted wherever a
.Ar timestamp
is expected:
.Ql HH:MM
and
.Ql HH:MM:SS
are interpreted as times on the current date;
.Ql yyyy-mm-ddTHH:MM
and
.Ql yyyy-mm-dd HH:MM
.Pq with a space instead of Ql T
are treated as if seconds were
.Ql :00 ;
.Ql yyyy-mm-dd
alone is treated as midnight
.Pq Ql T00:00:00 .
Multiple sessions may be active simultaneously.
.Pp
Wherever a
.Ar duration
is expected, the accepted forms are: a plain integer
.Pq interpreted as minutes, e.g. Ql 90 ,
.Ql Xh
.Pq e.g. Ql 2h ,
.Ql Ym
.Pq e.g. Ql 45m ,
or
.Ql XhYm
.Pq e.g. Ql 1h30m .
The suffix letters are case-insensitive.
.Pp
User-facing output displays timestamps in a simplified form:
seconds and the
.Ql T
separator are omitted
.Pq e.g.\& Ql 2026-03-19 12:16 ,
and timestamps from the current date show only the time
.Pq e.g.\& Ql 12:16 .
The
.Cm last
command shows full ISO\ 8601 timestamps for inspection.
.Pp
.Nm
offers a shell alias
.Sq c
that you can inject via
.Ql clk alias
for faster invocation.
.Ss Core workflow
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm in Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp Op Cm on Ar description
Clock in to a work session labeled with
.Ar tag .
Tags are single tokens
.Pq no spaces or tabs
and may use
.Ql .\&
as a hierarchical separator
.Pq e.g., Ql pm.bills .
Tags must not be purely numeric.
.Pp
Optionally specify when the session started via
.Cm minus Ar duration
.Pq that much time ago
or
.Cm at Ar timestamp
.Pq an exact ISO 8601 timestamp .
Optionally attach a description with
.Cm on Ar description .
The
.Cm on
keyword consumes all remaining arguments.
.Pp
If a session for the same tag is already active, the command fails.
Sessions with different tags may be active concurrently.
.It Cm out Op Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp Op Cm on Ar description
Clock out of the active session for
.Ar tag .
If exactly one session is active,
.Ar tag
may be omitted and is inferred automatically.
If multiple sessions are active,
.Ar tag
is required.
.Pp
If a description is provided via
.Cm on ,
it overrides any description set at clock-in.
If the session is currently paused, the pause is finalized
.Pq pause duration added to break time
before computing the session length.
.It Cm switch Ar new-tag Op Cm from Ar old-tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp Op Cm on Ar description
End one session and start another atomically.
The switch timestamp is both the end time of the old session and the
start time of the new one.
.Pp
.Cm from Ar old-tag
specifies which active session to close.
If omitted and exactly one session is active, it is inferred.
.Cm on Ar description
applies to the session being closed.
.It Bro Cm pause | Cm p Brc Op Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp
Pause an active session.
The session must not already be paused.
.Cm minus Ar duration
sets the pause start to that much time ago.
If
.Ar tag
is omitted and exactly one session is active, it is inferred.
.It Bro Cm resume | Cm r Brc Op Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp
Resume a paused session.
The pause duration is added to the session's accumulated break time.
.Cm minus Ar duration
sets the resume point to that much time ago.
.Cm at Ar timestamp
sets the resume point to an explicit time.
.It Bro Cm resume-focus | Cm R Brc Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp
Resume the specified session and pause all other active (non-paused) sessions.
If the target session is already running (not paused), it is left as-is and only the
other sessions are paused.
The tag is required.
.Cm minus Ar duration
and
.Cm at Ar timestamp
set the timestamp used for both the resume and the pauses.
The entire operation is a single undo step.
.It Bro Cm unpause | Cm up Brc Op Ar tag
Cancel a pause without adding break time.
Useful when a pause was started by mistake.
Does not affect the undo stack.
.El
.Ss Record management
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm add Ar tag Cm for Ar duration Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp Op Cm on Ar description
Add a completed session of
.Ar duration
length directly to the log, ending at the current time
.Pq or at the time specified by Cm minus No or Cm at .
The start time is back-calculated from the end time and duration.
.It Cm add Ar duration Op Cm to Ar tag
Add
.Ar duration
of time to an active session by moving its start time backwards.
If
.Cm to Ar tag
is omitted and exactly one session is active, it is inferred.
.It Bro Cm add-break | Cm ab Brc Ar duration Op Cm to Ar tag
Add
.Ar duration
of break time to an active session.
The session must not be currently paused.
If
.Cm to Ar tag
is omitted, the tag is inferred when unambiguous.
.It Cm extend Op Ar tag Op Cm minus Ar duration | Cm at Ar timestamp | Cm by Ar duration
Extend the last completed session to the current time, or to the time
specified by
.Cm minus
or
.Cm at ,
or by a fixed duration using
.Cm by .
If
.Ar tag
is given, extend the most recent completed session with that tag instead;
an error is raised if that tag currently has an active session.
When using
.Cm minus
or
.Cm at ,
the new end time must be at or after the original end time.
.Cm by Ar duration
shifts the end timestamp forward by exactly that much time.
.It Bro Cm remove | Cm pop Brc Op Fl Ar n
Without an index, removes the last record from the log
.Pq whether active or completed
and displays the removed record.
With
.Fl Ar n ,
removes the nth-to-last completed session
.Pq same negative-index convention as Cm edit and Cm reactivate .
.It Bro Cm reactivate | Cm ra Brc Fl Ar n
Convert a completed session back to active.
.Fl Ar n
is a negative index counting back from the most recent completed session:
.Fl 1
is the most recent,
.Fl 2
is second-to-last, and so on.
The session's start time, tag, accumulated break time, and description are
preserved; end time, length, and pause state are cleared.
Fails if the same tag already has an active session.
.El
.Ss Editing records
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm edit
With no arguments, opens an interactive TUI for browsing and editing records.
Displays all active sessions plus the most recent completed sessions (up to 10 rows).
Use arrow keys to navigate, Enter to select a record, and
.Sy q
to quit.
When editing time-related fields interactively, the TUI prompts for which field
should absorb the change.
Requires a terminal.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm tag Ar new-tag
Change the tag of the specified record.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm start Ar timestamp
Change the start time.
Recalculates length on completed records.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm end Ar timestamp Op Fl -adjust Cm active | Cm break
Change the end time.
Only valid on completed records.
By default
.Pq Fl -adjust Cm active ,
recalculates active time.
With
.Fl -adjust Cm break ,
keeps active time fixed and recalculates break time.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm active Ar duration Fl -adjust Cm start | Cm end | Cm break
Set active time directly.
.Ar duration
may be an integer (minutes) or a string like
.Dq 1h30m ,
.Dq 2h ,
or
.Dq 45m .
Requires
.Fl -adjust
to specify which field absorbs the change:
.Cm start
pushes the start time,
.Cm end
pushes the end time (done sessions only),
.Cm break
adjusts break time.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm break Ar duration Op Fl -adjust Cm active | Cm start | Cm end
Set break time.
.Ar duration
accepts the same formats as
.Cm active .
By default
.Pq Fl -adjust Cm active ,
recalculates active time.
With
.Fl -adjust Cm start ,
pushes the start time.
With
.Fl -adjust Cm end ,
pushes the end time (done sessions only).
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm pause Bro Ar timestamp | Cm clear Brc
Set or clear the paused-at timestamp on an active record.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm on Ar description
Change the description.
All arguments after
.Cm on
are collected as the description.
.It Cm edit Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc Cm delete
Delete the record entirely.
.El
.Pp
The index uses the same signed convention as the
.Nm Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc
single-record shortcut:
a negative index
.Fl Ar n
counts back from the most recent completed session
.Pq Fl 1 No = most recent done ;
a positive index
.Ar n
counts forward from the oldest active session
.Pq Ar 1 No = oldest active .
All edit operations save an undo snapshot.
Non-delete edits show the record before and after the change for comparison.
.Ss Viewing records
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Bro Cm status | Cm s Brc
Show all active sessions with their tag, start time, elapsed active time,
break time, pause state, and description.
If no sessions are active, prints
.Dq \&No active sessions .
.It Bro Cm last | Cm l Brc Op Ar n
Show the last
.Ar n
completed sessions, one per line, with their
.Fl 1 , Fl 2 , No ...
.Fl Ar n
index prefixes.
.Ar n
must be a positive integer; the default is 1.
If
.Ar n
exceeds the number of completed sessions, all available are shown
.Pq no error .
.Cm last
only looks at the done pool; active sessions are never shown.
Full ISO\ 8601 timestamps are shown for inspection.
.It Bro Fl Ar n | Ar n Brc
Show a single session by index.
A negative index
.Fl Ar n
counts back from the most recent completed session:
.Fl 1
is the most recent done session,
.Fl 2
is second-to-last, and so on.
A positive index
.Ar n
counts forward from the oldest active session:
.Ar 1
is the oldest active session,
.Ar 2
is second-oldest, and so on.
The index prefix in the output
.Pq e.g.\& Fl 3 No or No +2
matches the convention used by
.Cm edit .
.Pp
If a negative index is followed by a time unit, however,
.Nm Fl Ar n Ar unit
is interpreted as a
.Cm view
range
.Pq e.g., Ql clk -1 month = Ql clk view -1 month
rather than a single-record lookup.
.It Cm log
Open the log file in
.Ev VISUAL ,
.Ev EDITOR ,
or
.Xr vi 1 .
.El
.Ss Analysis
The
.Cm view
command summarizes sessions over a time range with optional filtering.
The
.Cm view
keyword is optional: any
.Ar range
may also be given directly as the top-level command, e.g.
.Ql clk today ,
.Ql clk past 3 days ,
.Ql clk -1 month ,
or
.Ql clk from 2026-03-01 to 2026-03-15 .
.Pp
.D1 Nm Bro Cm view | Cm v Brc Ar range Op Ar filter
.D1 Nm Ar range Op Ar filter
.Pp
.Ar range
is one of:
.Bl -tag -width indent -compact
.It Bro Cm all | Cm today | Cm yesterday Brc
.It Bro Fl Ar n | Cm this Brc Ar unit Op Cm through No ...
.It Cm past Op Ar n Ar unit Op Cm before Ar timestamp | Cm before Cm minus Ar duration
.It Cm from Ar timestamp Cm to Ar timestamp
.El
.Pp
.Ar filter
is:
.Bl -tag -width indent -compact
.It Op Cm for Ar tag Ns , Ns Ar tag Ns , Ns ... Op Cm by Bro Cm day | Cm week | Cm month | Cm session Brc
.El
.Pp
.Ar unit
is one of
.Bro Cm hour(s) | Cm day(s) | Cm week(s) | Cm month(s) | Cm year(s) Brc .
.Ss Range details
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm all
Summarize all sessions in the log.
.It Cm today
Summarize sessions from midnight today until now.
.It Cm yesterday
Summarize sessions from midnight yesterday until midnight today.
.It Bro Fl Ar n | Cm this Brc Ar unit Op Cm through No ...
View sessions for a calendar period relative to the current one.
.Cm this
is an alias for
.Fl 0 .
.Cm today
is equivalent to
.Fl 0 Cm day ;
.Cm yesterday
is equivalent to
.Fl 1 Cm day .
When
.Cm today
or
.Cm yesterday
is used, the unit is implied and may be omitted.
Weeks start on Monday.
.Fl 0 Cm week
covers Monday of the current week until now;
.Fl 1 Cm week
covers last Monday through Sunday.
.Fl 0 Cm month
covers the 1st of the current month until now;
.Fl 1 Cm month
covers the entire previous calendar month.
.Pp
The optional
.Cm through
modifier extends the range to include all of the specified end period.
For example,
.Ql view -2 weeks through -1 week
spans from two Mondays ago through the end of last Sunday.
The
.Cm through
period must be more recent than the starting period.
The same aliases
.Pq Cm this , Cm today , Cm yesterday
are accepted after
.Cm through .
Start and end units may differ
.Pq e.g., Ql -2 months through -1 week .
.It Cm past Op Ar n Ar unit Op Cm before No ...
Summarize sessions over the past
.Ar n
hours, days, weeks, months, or years
.Pq default 1 .
Both singular and plural unit forms are accepted
.Pq e.g., Cm day No or Cm days .
One month equals 30 days; one year equals 365 days.
.Pp
The
.Cm before
modifier anchors the lookback window to a point other than now:
.Cm before Ar timestamp
anchors to the given timestamp, and
.Cm before Cm minus Ar duration
anchors to that much time ago.
.It Cm from Ar timestamp Cm to Ar timestamp
Summarize sessions in an explicit time range.
.El
.Ss Filter details
All
.Cm view
ranges accept optional filter suffixes:
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm for Ar tag Ns , Ns Ar tag Ns , Ns ...
Filter results to only sessions matching the given tag(s).
Multiple tags can be specified separated by commas
.Pq e.g., Ql dev,pm,admin .
A tag ending with a dot matches the tag itself and all its children
.Pq e.g., Ql dev. No matches dev , dev.frontend , dev.backend.api .
When multiple tags are given, their times are combined.
.It Cm by Bro Cm day | Cm week | Cm month | Cm session Brc
Group results into a horizontal bar chart by day, week, month, or session
.Pq one bar per clk record .
When used without
.Cm for ,
aggregates all tags into each bucket.
Displays summary statistics (mean, median, stddev, skewness) and total time below the chart.
The total is shown in minutes and, when 60 or more, also as hours and minutes.
.El
.Pp
Without
.Cm by ,
.Cm view
displays a table of tags with total minutes, hours, and percentages.
Active sessions whose start time falls within the range are excluded
from totals and noted separately.
.Ss Utilities
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Cm undo
Undo the last mutating operation.
Displays a human-readable diff of the change.
Only one level of undo is supported; each new mutation overwrites the
undo snapshot.
.It Cm redo
Redo the last undone operation.
Displays a human-readable diff of the change.
.It Cm help
Show this man page.
Falls back to a synopsis if the man page is not installed.
.It Cm alias
Inject an alias
.Sq c
for
.Nm
into the current shell's rc file.
Detects the default shell and appends
.Ql alias c='clk'
to
.Pa ~/.bashrc
(bash) or
.Pa ~/.zshrc
(zsh).
If
.Sq c
is already defined as a command, function, or alias,
.Nm
reports the conflict and exits.
.El
.Sh EXAMPLES
.Ss Basic workflow
Clock in to a task, check on it, and clock out:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk in dev
$ clk status
$ clk out
.Ed
.Pp
When only one session is active, the tag can be omitted from
.Cm out ,
.Cm pause ,
.Cm resume ,
and other commands that operate on an active session.
.Ss Timestamps and descriptions
Start a session that began 15 minutes ago, with a note:
.Dl $ clk in dev minus 15 on fixing auth bug
.Pp
Clock out at a specific time:
.Dl $ clk out at 17:30
.Pp
Timestamps accept several shorthand forms:
.Ql HH:MM ,
.Ql yyyy-mm-dd ,
and
.Ql yyyy-mm-ddTHH:MM
all work wherever a timestamp is expected.
.Ss Pausing and resuming
Take a break during a session:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk pause
$ clk resume
.Ed
.Pp
If you paused by mistake, cancel it without recording break time:
.Dl $ clk unpause
.Ss Switching tasks
End one session and start another atomically:
.Dl $ clk switch pm
.Pp
If multiple sessions are active, specify which one to close:
.Dl $ clk switch pm from dev
.Ss Multiple concurrent sessions
You can clock in to several tags at once:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk in dev
$ clk in pm
$ clk status
$ clk out pm
$ clk out dev
.Ed
.Pp
When more than one session is active, the tag is required for
.Cm out ,
.Cm pause ,
and
.Cm resume .
.Ss Adding past sessions
Log a 45-minute meeting that just ended:
.Dl $ clk add pm for 45
.Pp
Log a session that ended at a specific time:
.Dl $ clk add pm for 30 at 14:00 on standup
.Pp
Add 10 minutes to the current session (moves start time back):
.Dl $ clk add 10
.Ss Viewing time
See what you did today, this week, or over any range
.Pq the Cm view No keyword is optional :
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk today
$ clk this week
$ clk past 3 days
$ clk from 2026-03-01 to 2026-03-15
.Ed
.Pp
Filter by tag and see a bar chart grouped by day:
.Dl $ clk this month for dev by day
.Pp
Combine multiple tags:
.Dl $ clk past 2 weeks for dev,pm by week
.Pp
Match a tag and all its children with a trailing dot:
.Dl $ clk this month for dev. by session
.Pp
This matches
.Ql dev ,
.Ql dev.frontend ,
.Ql dev.backend.api ,
and so on.
.Ss Inspecting and editing records
Show the last 5 completed records (indices
.Fl 5
through
.Fl 1 ) :
.Dl $ clk last 5
.Pp
Show just the second-to-last completed record:
.Dl $ clk -2
.Pp
Show just the oldest active session:
.Dl $ clk 1
.Pp
Browse and edit records interactively:
.Dl $ clk edit
.Pp
Change the tag on the most recent record:
.Dl $ clk edit -1 tag admin
.Pp
Fix the start time of the second-to-last record:
.Dl $ clk edit -2 start 09:15
.Pp
Change end time, adjusting break time instead of active time:
.Dl $ clk edit -1 end 17:30 --adjust break
.Pp
Set active time directly, pushing start back to match:
.Dl $ clk edit -1 active 2h30m --adjust start
.Pp
Set break time using a duration string:
.Dl $ clk edit -1 break 1h15m
.Pp
Delete a record:
.Dl $ clk edit -3 delete
.Ss Undo mistakes
Every mutation can be undone (and re-done):
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk undo
$ clk redo
.Ed
.Ss Shell alias
For faster invocation, install a one-letter alias:
.Bd -literal -offset indent
$ clk alias
$ c in dev
.Ed
.Sh ENVIRONMENT
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Ev XDG_DATA_HOME
Log file location.
Defaults to
.Pa ~/.local/share .
The log is stored at
.Pa ${XDG_DATA_HOME}/clk/clk.tsv .
.It Ev VISUAL , Ev EDITOR
Editor used by
.Cm log .
Falls back to
.Xr vi 1 .
.El
.Sh FILES
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It Pa ${XDG_DATA_HOME}/clk/clk.tsv
The time-tracking log.
Tab-separated, eight fields per record.
.It Pa ${XDG_DATA_HOME}/clk/clk.tsv.undo
Snapshot before the last mutating operation.
.It Pa ${XDG_DATA_HOME}/clk/clk.tsv.redo
Snapshot before the last undo.
.El
.Sh EXIT STATUS
.Bl -tag -width indent
.It 0
No error.
.It 1
Argument error.
.It 2
Log access / modification error.
.It 3
Incompatible operating system.
.It 4
Date conversion error.
.It 5
Invalid log state.
.It 6
Summarization failed.
.El
.Sh AUTHORS
.An poiurewq
